It was just a few years before The Great Famine in Ireland, which wiped out approximately 25 percent of the population due to mass starvation, according to Vicki Dawson from Findmypast.

'The area was hit quite hard by the famine between 1845 and 1852. He was transported a few years before it hit, so he may not have even survived if he hadn't stolen the pigs,' Ms Dawson said.

'If he hadn't come here, Ned Kelly may not have been born.'

The move would become etched in Australia's history with his son Ned set to become the nation's most iconic criminal.

'His father was given his certificate of freedom and moved to Melbourne where he met Ned's mother,' Ms Dawson said. 

